I will say that every web site is designed to target a specific market segment.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="span"> Based on this there are different constrains to deliver a easy to use web site.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration"> First all the pages in the web site must have the same architecture or look and feel (a good front end), the logic behind the pages, the technology (client side or server side), and basically what the page is supposed to do.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="8" relname="condition"> If it is a marketing web site</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="10" relname="span"> all the graphics and flash presentations must be displayed fast,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="9" relname="condition"> if it is a shopping car</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="11" relname="span"> then the main functionality is to post and get information from/to server.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="7" relname="concession"> 
we can discuss a lot of these points</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="14" relname="span"> but we also need to be aware that web designers are under the supervision of manager and that sometimes the delivered web design was not the original designed by the architects, but by the managers.</segment>
